# WHAT IT IS
#   polygram is a Telegram daemon + Claude Code plugin that
#   gives each Telegram chat its own persistent Claude
#   session (via `claude --resume`).  Intended as a
#   migration path for OpenClaw users — OpenClaw dropped
#   Claude support; the official `telegram@claude-plugins-
#   official` plugin is single-session (one bot, one shared
#   context); polygram restores OpenClaw's per-chat-session
#   ergonomics on top of the `claude` CLI.
#
#   Architecture (one Node process per bot — `N bots = N
#   processes` for crash isolation):
#     Telegram (grammy long-poll)
#         → polygram receives message
#         → looks up per-chat config (model, effort, agent,
#            cwd)
#         → sends to persistent `claude` child process via
#            stdin (stream-json multi-turn)
#         → reads response from stdout (stream-json)
#         → sends reply to Telegram
#         → writes every in/out message to per-bot SQLite
#            (source of truth)
#
#   Per-chat in-chat commands:
#     /model <model>                 Switch the active Claude
#                                    model for this chat
#     /effort <level>                Set Claude reasoning
#                                    effort (low | medium |
#                                    high)
#     /config                        Show this chat's config
#
#   Companion bins:
#     polygram-doctor    — operational health check (config,
#                          token, reachability, membership,
#                          recent-error trail; safe to run
#                          against a live bot)
#     polygram-ipc       — IPC round-trip smoke probe
#     polygram-split-db  — Phase 8 migration: split a shared
#                          `bridge.db` into per-bot DBs
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from polygram.js +
#                       lib/config-scope.js + scripts/
#                       {doctor,ipc-smoke,split-db}.js;
#                       extracted via `gh api repos/shumkov/
#                       polygram/contents/...`)
#
#   polygram --bot <NAME> [--db <PATH>]
#
#   Required:
#     --bot <NAME>                   Bot name (must exist in
#                                    `config.bots`) — every
#                                    polygram process serves
#                                    exactly one bot
#
#   Optional:
#     --db <PATH>                    SQLite database path
#                                    override [default:
#                                    `<bot>.db` resolved
#                                    against $PWD]
#
#   Environment variables (every polygram process reads):
#     POLYGRAM_CONFIG <PATH>         Config JSON file path
#                                    (overrides default
#                                    `config.json`)
#     POLYGRAM_CLAUDE_BIN <PATH>     Path to the `claude` CLI
#                                    binary (default: claude
#                                    from PATH)
#     POLYGRAM_CHILD_HOME <PATH>     HOME directory for the
#                                    child claude process
#     POLYGRAM_INBOX <PATH>          Inbox directory
#                                    (forwarded messages)
#     POLYGRAM_IPC_SECRET <STR>      Shared IPC secret for
#                                    polygram-ipc handshake
#     POLYGRAM_STICKERS <PATH>       Stickers map JSON path
#                                    [default: stickers.json]
#
#   ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   polygram-doctor --bot <NAME> [OPTIONS]
#
#   Required:
#     --bot <NAME>                   Bot name to inspect
#
#   Options:
#     --roundtrip                    Also do an outbound
#                                    round-trip
#                                    (IPC send → Telegram
#                                    → DB read-back).
#                                    Requires --to.
#     --to <CHAT-ID>                 Target chat ID for the
#                                    round-trip probe
#     --json                         Emit JSON output for
#                                    monitoring pipelines
#     --strict                       Treat warnings as
#                                    failures
#
#   Exit codes:
#     0  all checks passed (warnings allowed unless --strict)
#     1  at least one check failed
#     2  bad invocation / missing args
#
